=== Special Case: Bernoulli RVs ===

Suppose formula_10 and formula_11 for all &quot;i&quot;. This can occur when &quot;Xi&quot; are independent Bernoulli random variables, though they need not be identically distributed. Then we get the inequality
:formula_12
or equivalently,

formula_13

for all formula_14. This is a version of the additive Chernoff bound which is more general, since it allows for random variables that take values between zero and one, but also weaker, since the Chernoff bound gives a better tail bound when the random variables have small variance.

== General case of bounded from above random variables ==

Hoeffding&#x27;s inequality can be extended to the case of bounded from above random variables.

Let be independent random variables such that formula_15 and formula_16 almost surely. 
Denote by
:formula_17

Hoeffding&#x27;s inequality for bounded from above random variables states that for all formula_14,
:formula_19
In particular, if formula_20 for all formula_21,
then for all formula_14,
:formula_23

== General case of sub-Gaussian random variables ==

The proof of Hoeffding&#x27;s inequality can be generalized to any sub-Gaussian distribution. Recall that a random variable is called sub-Gaussian, if 

