==Usage==
===Confidence intervals===

Hoeffding&#x27;s inequality can be used to derive confidence intervals. We consider a coin that shows heads with probability and tails with probability . We toss the coin times, generating samples formula_42 (which are i.i.d Bernoulli random variables). The expected number of times the coin comes up heads is . Furthermore, the probability that the coin comes up heads at least times can be exactly quantified by the following expression:

:formula_43

where is the number of heads in coin tosses.

When for some , Hoeffding&#x27;s inequality bounds this probability by a term that is exponentially small in :

:formula_44

Since this bound holds on both sides of the mean, Hoeffding&#x27;s inequality implies that the number of heads that we see is concentrated around its mean, with exponentially small tail.

:formula_45

Thinking of formula_46 as the &quot;observed&quot; mean, this probability can be interpreted as the level of significance formula_47 (probability of making an error) for a confidence interval around formula_48 of size 2:

:formula_49

Finding for opposite inequality sign in the above, i.e. that violates inequality but not equality above, gives us:

:formula_50

Therefore, we require at least formula_51 samples to acquire a formula_52-confidence interval formula_53.

Hence, the cost of acquiring the confidence interval is sublinear in terms of confidence level and quadratic in terms of precision. Note that there are more efficient methods of estimating a confidence interval.

